revision.text:
[[Image:Zest a Citrus Fruit Intro.jpg|right|300px]]The zest of the citrus fruit is the colored skin that contains the essential oils of the fruit. Remove the zest from a citrus fruit and add it to cocktails, desserts, sauces and a wide variety of different dishes.
[[Category:Citrus Fruits]]

== Steps ==
=== Zest a Citrus Fruit with a Microplane ===
Using a microplane is the easiest way to remove the zest from an orange, lemon or lime.
#Wash your fruit under a stream of cool water.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 1.jpg}}
#Place your citrus fruit on a cutting board.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 2.jpg}}
#Position the microplane at a 45-degree angle and rest the fruit on top.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 3.jpg}}
#Push the fruit across the microplane to remove the zest.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 4.jpg}}
#Rotate the fruit as you run it across the microplane until all of the colored skin is gone. Be careful not to grate the bitter white pith.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 5.jpg}}
#Collect the grated zest and either add it to your recipe or place it in a small bowl for later use.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 6.jpg}}
#Wrap your fruit in plastic wrap and refrigerate it for another use.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 7.jpg}}
=== Zest a Citrus Fruit with a Zester ===

A zester removes the colored skin of the citrus fruit in long, curling strips. You can either leave the strips intact and use them for garnish, or you can chop the zest to add to your recipe.
#Wash your fruit under a stream of cool water.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 8.jpg}}
#Place your citrus fruit on a cutting board.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 9.jpg}}
#Position the zester on the top side of the fruit near the base of the fruit. The blades of the zester should be in contact with the zest.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 10.jpg}}
#Peel the zest from the fruit by pulling the zester toward you.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 11.jpg}}
#Rotate the fruit and continue to peel strips of zest until all of the zest has been removed. Do not remove the bitter white pith beneath.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 12.jpg}}
#Wrap the fruit in plastic wrap and refrigerate it for another use.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 13.jpg}}
#Gather the zest into a pile on your cutting board.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 14.jpg}}
#Finely chop the zest using your chef’s knife or paring knife. Alternatively, if you want to use the zest as a garnish, then leave it in long strips and don’t chop it.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 15.jpg}}
#Collect the zest and either add it to your recipe or place it in a small bowl for later use.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 16.jpg}}
=== Zest a Citrus Fruit with a Vegetable Peeler or Paring Knife ===

If you don’t own a microplane or zester, then you can carefully remove the zest from a citrus fruit using a knife or a vegetable peeler.
#Wash the citrus fruit under a stream of cool water.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 17.jpg}}
#Place the fruit on your cutting board and position your vegetable peeler or paring knife on top of the fruit near the base.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 18.jpg}}
#Peel wide strips of zest from the fruit by pulling the knife or the vegetable peeler upward.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 19.jpg}}
#Chop the zest into small pieces using your paring knife.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 20.jpg}}
#Reserve the fruit for another use.{{largeimage|Zest a Citrus Fruit Step 21.jpg}}

== Video ==
{{Video:Zest a Citrus Fruit|}}

== Tips ==
*An orange with the zest removed can still be consumed. All citrus fruit can still be used for juicing even when the zest is removed, so do not discard fruit when the skin is gone.
*Store leftover zest in the refrigerator for two or three days in a sealed container. If you want to store zest longer, then freeze zest in single tablespoon portions. The zest will keep in the freezer for up to a year.
*If you’re using both the zest and the juice of a citrus fruit in your recipe, then be sure to zest first. After all of the juice has been removed, removing zest becomes challenging.
*If you don’t own a zester or a microplane, then you can place your citrus fruit against the fine side of a box grater and grate it to remove the zest. However, you’ll need to remove the zest slowly and gently to avoid grating off the bitter white pith.

== Things You'll Need ==
*Cutting board
*Microplane
*Small bowl
*Zester

